commitResults.messageTitle: Increment Duke to Level-1
commitResults.messageBody:
Recustomize the chatbot name.
Add basic echo behavior indicated by the level requirement.
Recustomize the chatbot text UI.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add a todo class to store the todo items
Todo: change from accessing from class to accessing from instances
Increment Lihua to Level 2
commitResults.messageBody: Using Todo class to complete the functionality in Lihua.java

commitResults.messageTitle: Integrate a new Item class representing tasks into the application
Refactor Todo class name to make more sense
Integrate get done feature to Item and Todos
Add a class providing methods to check format of input
Add handling for index out of bound exception for the feature of getting things done.
Fix typo in message to print out
Add get done feature to main program
Refactor with more reasonable names
Add 3 new Task's children classes
Update documentation for 3 Task classes
Update/Add helper class for user input checking and extracting
Add task adding methods in Tasks class
Add print functionality for 3 task adding
Fix bug (add error handling for format checking)
Formatting code
Use polymorphism to reduce repetitive code
Add text ui testing scripts
Add handling for wrong/missing argument of 'done'
Add exception handling, increment to level 5
Add additional testing scripts for level 5
Add a help command with Enumeration of commands
Add save functionality using JSON Simple
commitResults.messageBody:
The task bot can only save the tasks temporarily.

A user would expect his/her tasks to be stored permanently, so that he/she can retrieve the tasks in the future.

Let's update Lihua so that the tasks can be stored in hard disk and loaded later.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add strict date formatting for deadline
commitResults.messageBody:
Deadline accepts all forms of string as initialization input.

Some meaningless inputs may be accepted, e.g. deadline /by haha.

Let's update the Deadline class and propagate the changes to let
deadline accepts only 'yyyy-mm-dd' format dates.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add strict date formatting for event
commitResults.messageBody:
Event accepts all forms of string as initialization input.

Some meaningless inputs may be accepted, e.g. event /at haha.

Let's update the Event class and propagate the changes to let
event accepts only 'yyyy-mm-dd' format dates.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add functionality to list tasks on a specific date
commitResults.messageBody:
The date associated with a task (if applicable) is only a record with no
utility.

User would expect a function to search tasks by date.

Let's implement this function and propogate changes.

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix bug related to date parsing
commitResults.messageBody:
The time field of JSON object for ToDo object is set to be an empty
string.

Calling LocalDate.parse("") would result in an exception.

Let's update the implementation so that the `LocalDate.parse()` will not
be called for ToDo objects.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add Storage, Ui components
commitResults.messageBody:
Ui and storage functions are embedded inside other program logic.

This will cause the code to violate OOP standards and become less readable.

Let's integrate Storage and Ui functions into classes of their own.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add Command, Parser components
commitResults.messageBody:
Commands are explictly handled. Understanding of command is also explicit.

This would introduce lengthy if-else block as well as repetitive String
split operations, which is not very readable, maintainable, and efficient.

Let's follow [AddressBook Level 2](https://github.com/se-edu/addressbook-level2)
 style and integrate Command and Parser classes into the application.

commitResults.messageTitle: Remove redundant code
commitResults.messageBody:
The application contains a lot of redundant/unused code after refactoring.

Unsued code reduces readability, and hampers the reasoning of logic.

Let's remove (part of) the redundant code from the project.

commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor classes to form various packages
commitResults.messageBody:
All classes are inside one directory.

Not easy to classify the classess, thus reducing readability and
hampering modulization.

By dividing classes into packages, the code becomes easier to maintain.

Let's follow a packaging style similer to [address-book level-2](https://github.com/se-edu/addressbook-level2).

commitResults.messageTitle: Delete unused files
commitResults.messageBody:
The four customized exception files have no implementation and are not used.

Unused files hampers readability and clarity of the whole project.

Let's delete the four files. Self-defined exception classes can be done
at a later stage.

commitResults.messageTitle: Create simple JUnit tests on static fileds mainly
commitResults.messageBody:
No JUnit tests are included.

No testing of important fields or methods would result in serious bugs or
unexpected behavior of code.

Let's use JUnit 5.4 to test some of the static fields of classes.

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix index out of bound bug for command 'done'
commitResults.messageBody:
The index is zero-based.

Zero-based indexing may be confusing to non-programmers.

Let's modify the indexing for 'done' so that it is 1-based.

commitResults.messageTitle: Update gradle support
commitResults.messageBody:
The gradle class & dependency name are default.

Default names are not compatible with the project.

Let's update build.gradle so that the dependency and class name are supported.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add javadoc for all classes
commitResults.messageBody:
No/incomplete javadoc is provided.

Missing javadoc would affect the readability and maintenance of the code.

Let's add javadoc to our application.

commitResults.messageTitle: Tweak the code to follow code standards
commitResults.messageBody:
The code style is mostly correct, with few exceptions because of carelessness.

Making the code style standard is better.

Let's update the style a bit so that the code basically abides the standard.

commitResults.messageTitle: Modify welcome and good back emonji
commitResults.messageBody:
The emonji is not displaying properly in windows terminal.

Let's update the emonji so that it gets displayed properly.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add find by keyword functionality
commitResults.messageBody:
The application only supports list tasks by time (if applicable).

The user would want to search tasks by name/keyword.

Let's integrate the find by keyword functionality into our application.

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix issues in regression testing
commitResults.messageBody:
After adding the find functionality, the regression testing fails

Testing failure means potential bugs.

Let's fix the regression testing issue.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add checkstyle files and make style changes
commitResults.messageBody:
The code style check is done manually through eyeballs.

Doing code style check manually is time-consuming and error-prone.

Let's integrate auto-checkstyle using gradle.

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix issues with jar file using gradle
commitResults.messageBody:
After the code is refactored, the jar file encounters "ClassNotFoundException" upon start.

This is a bug caused by java file packaging.

Let's fix this issue by unpackage Lihua.java file.

commitResults.messageTitle: Enable assertion in runtime
commitResults.messageBody:
Assertion in runtime is not supported by build.gradle.

Sometimes such assertion is necessary to ensure correctness of program.

Let's configure the build.gradle file to allow assertions.

commitResults.messageTitle: Integrate javaFX tutorial GUI into Lihua
commitResults.messageBody:
Lihua is implemented in a CLI application way.

A GUI will make the app easire to use for users, as users can see
the feedback in a more friendly manner.

Although it is far from complete, let's integrate the GUI features the
javaFX tutorial (https://se-education.org/guides/tutorials/javaFx.html)
introduces into the current Lihua project.

commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor classes to fit in different packages
commitResults.messageBody:
All newly created GUI classes are put under package lihua directly.

This arrangement of classes are not easy to maintain and manage.

It's better to integrate all classes into different packages, based on their functionalities.

commitResults.messageTitle: Integrate Lihua's original functionality into tutorial GUI
commitResults.messageBody:
The tutorial GUI only supports echo functionality.

Echo functionality is, of course, not adequate.

Let's integrate almost all Lihua's original functionalities into the naive GUI.
The exit command is not supported right now since the mechanism of
exit command is different from normal ones.

commitResults.messageTitle: Increment GUI
commitResults.messageBody:
The GUI style follows the tutorial style.

The GUI is not unique to Lihua.

Let's chaneg some default style setting of GUI so that Lihua looks unique.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add minor changes to GUI; update gradle JavaFX version
Fix styling issues pointed out by peers
commitResults.messageBody:
The styling is mostly ok, except some minor details.

Peers pointed the details out for me during PR review practice.

Let's update the code style to comply to good java code standards.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add assertions to Lihua
commitResults.messageBody:
Assertions do not exists anywhere in code.

Liberal use of assertions can reduce the likelyhood of bugs.

Let's integrate some important assertions we make about the code in Lihua.

commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor code to make the code have better code quality
commitResults.messageBody:
The code follows basic java coding standards, but some of the code
is written in a way that does not follow best practices of code quality.

Code of poor code quality can propogate the messy effects to the future.

Let's refactor the code to make it have better code quality.

commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor code to make the code have better code quality
commitResults.messageBody:
The code follows basic java coding standards, but some of the code
is written in a way that does not follow best practices of code quality.

Code of poor code quality can propogate the messy effects to the future.

Let's refactor the code to make it have better code quality.

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix a bug in data storage
commitResults.messageBody:
Incorrect exception handling leads to the console to print error information
when initially there is no data file.

This should not happen since no data file initially should be a normal
situation instead of an error.

Let's update Storage.java to fix this bug.

commitResults.messageTitle: Remove all text-ui-test files
commitResults.messageBody:
The text-ui-test files are to be used to test the text ui of the application.

This testing is no longer needed since there is already a GUI available.

Let's drop related files to make our workspace cleaner.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add C-Sort functionality to the project
commitResults.messageBody:
The bot lists down task in a FIFO order.

A more natural order may be order the tasks by name. Also, if additonal
tag -time is provided to command 'list', all the tasks with time information
will be listed in chronological order.

Let's integrate this feature and propograte changes.

commitResults.messageTitle: Give credit to reused code for GUI
commitResults.messageBody:
The code for GUI, though taken from the tutorials provided, is not given credit.

It is best to give credit to the author of them.

Let's give credit to the author for code snippets taken from him.

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix issues in regressions
commitResults.messageBody:
After previous incrementation or  sorting functionality, the current test cases fail.

Failure in test cases indicates potential bugs, or some regression issues. It is better
to handle them as soon as possible.

Let's fix the test (mainly for message testing) for the project.

commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor code by arranging packages in a more reasonable manner
Add streams to some simple task loop handling in Tasks.java
Update styles to conform with CheckStyle
Add different backgrounds for Lihua and user
commitResults.messageBody:
The background is the same for both enitites.

It will be more distinguishable if the backgrounds are different.

Let us update the background of dialog box so that Lihua and user
have different background colors.

commitResults.messageTitle: Beautify the profile icon
commitResults.messageBody:
The icon is directly taken from a picture.

The GUI would be more beautiful if the icon can have a rounded, colored, shaded effect.

Let us update the GUI for dialog to achieve this effect.

commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor GUI code to remove unused parts
Modify the background color for GUI
Let bot change background color when the user input is incorrect to remind user
commitResults.messageBody:
The bot does not change background color.

User may want to be reminded if their input is not in the correct format.

Let us change the code so that the bot can change background color if the
user input is incorrect. Right now we do not care how the checking if input
is correct, but we focus on how to change color. The checking will be done in
the next commit.

commitResults.messageTitle: Update Lihua to allow CommandResult containing a field indicating of whether the user input is in the correct format or not
commitResults.messageBody:
The background judge of Lihua is always going to give an 'error' background.

We want our Lihua to give 'error' background only if the user input has an 'error'.

Let us update CommandResult and propagate changes to accomodate the functionality.

commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor code to follow check style guidance
Update README.MD of ip/docs
Make tasks listed in alphabetic ordering
Update ip/docs/README.md for the product website
commitResults.messageBody:
The product website is not complete.

The product webstie will provide enough information if it is complete.

Let us update ip/docs/README.md and complete missing information.

Fix README issues (table not correctly rendered in published view)
